In the next year (188) Cato acted in the senate with the party which tried unsuccessfully to refuse the triumph to the two consuls of 189, M. Fulvius Nobilior and Cn. Manlius Vulso, the former of whom bad gained none but trifling advantages over the Aetolians, while the latter bad disgraced the Roman name by making war without authorisation upon the Gauls of Asia Minor, and had also suffered a humiliating defeat from some Thracian robber hands on his homeward march. Not disheartened by their ill fortune, Cato and his friends determined to strike at higher game. L.
